@incollection{benhamou2010orientation,
abstract = {Orientation and navigation processes are at the core of spatial behaviors. Considering various species, from bacteria to human beings, reveals a large diversity of orientation behaviors, in terms of information sources and mechanisms. Some rely on physical or chemical gradients, some others learn specific routes using visual beacons or proprioceptive information, whereas still others rely on spatial representations to memorize a goal location with respect to their own body's location or to some environmental features. Although elementary orientation mechanisms correspond to simple getting-there procedures and more complex navigation behaviors rest on knowing-where processes, animals have often evolved original navigation solutions mixing these two types of components. In this article, we discuss how these various orientation and navigation processes can be conceptually unified in a consistent theoretical framework.},
